{"name":"Amorphous","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">Not every entity is constrained by a rigid skeleton; some organisms </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">possess a malleable shape, or are made of a host of smaller </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">beings, and can alter their forms as desired or due to changing </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">environmental conditions. A creature with this trait may increase </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">or decrease its Size trait value by 1 as a Free Action (though doing </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">so does not change its movement values). A creature with this trait </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">also has the Crawler trait.</span></span></p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature is a formless blob, and slow."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"nOI8SCj5O7ZxGYnJ"}
{"name":"Amphibious","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>The creature can breathe water as well as air and can stay underwater indefinitely without the need to surface. If this trait is taken by a creature with the ability to breathe another substance other than air (i.e., water, ammonia, carbon-dioxide, etc.) then it can breathe air as well as its native atmosphere.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature can breathe underwater."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"4qISQxGhJQZlA0BL"}
{"name":"Auto-stabilised","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>For exceptionally large creatures, even the most unstable of heavy weapons mean little compared to their huge limbs, gripping talons, or sheer bulk. These beings always count as braced when firing heavy weapons and therefore may fire a weapon on full or semi-automatic without taking the Brace action first, and not suffer any penalties to hit.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Always counts as braced."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"wsnrYiJx3qq0UPcp"}
{"name":"Baneful Presence","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>The creature&rsquo;s very existence is anathema to nearby mortals, and permeates its surroundings with the taint of the unnatural. All characters suffer a &ndash;10 penalty to Willpower tests taken while within X metres of the creature.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature inflicts Willpower penalty to nearby characters"},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"lFDOEup89EyjqyMa"}
{"name":"Bestial","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait is animalistic, tending to behave instinctively rather than rationally. No matter how high its Intelligence score is, it is still bestial. A creature with this trait never needs to make a Survival test whilst in its natural habitat. Unless starving or desperate, a Bestial creature must make a Challenging (+0) Willpower test when frightened, startled, or injured. If it fails, the creature flees.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Automatically passes Survival skill tests, test Willpower to avoid flight."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"g8eMlKBy1Oz6ZeBe"}
{"name":"Blind","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Blind creatures automatically fail all tests based on vision, and automatically fail all Ballistic Skill tests. Such creatures take a &ndash;30 penalty to Weapon Skill tests and most other tests that ordinarily involve or are benefited by vision. Note that this trait indicates not only that the creature cannot see but that it also has no other senses which would provide the same benefit as eyes (such as Unnatural Senses). The Blind Fighting talent reduces the penalty to Weapon Skill tests as normal for Blind creatures, from &ndash;30 to &ndash;15.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Cannot see"},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"g8gYDEW5jOtH3TRk"}
{"name":"Brutal Charge","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait is often massive and powerful, nearly unstoppable in combat. When Charging, the creature deals an extra (X) points of damage on each hit it inflicts that turn.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Deals additional damage on a Charge"},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"0MGyqNbYOIpyOvcu"}
{"name":"Burrower","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait can move through solid objects by burrowing through them. The number in parentheses (X) indicates its speed when burrowing. Such creatures can burrow through soil, rock, sand, and so on, though some (expressed in the creature entry) can even burrow through metal. When a creature burrows, it leaves behind a tunnel. Characters with a Size trait value lower than the burrower can enter these areas without impediment. At the end of each round after the burrower passes, roll 1d10; on a result of 5 or lower, the tunnel collapses behind the creature.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Move by digging."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"9LLTB4sxorKTzwAS"}
{"name":"Crawler","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Worms, serpents, and similar creatures crawl and slither along the surface rather than walk upright. The base move for a creature with this trait is half its normal movement rate (round up) as determined by its Agility bonus, but it does not take penalties for moving over difficult terrain.</p>","source":"","benefit":"No penalties for moving over  difficult terrain."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"tC4I6bTDDZOhJZLT"}
{"name":"Daemonic","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Daemonic creatures are denizens of the Warp, but can manifest in real space either through sheer strength of will, hunger, or occult rituals. Creatures with this trait increase their Toughness bonus against all damage by the number indicated in the parentheses (X), in the same manner as an Unnatural Characteristic (see page 139), and stack if the latter also increases Toughness. This increase is negated by damage inflicted from force weapons, psychic powers, holy attacks, or other creatures with this trait. Daemonic creatures also have the Undying trait, and gain benefits when using psychic powers as detailed in Chapter VI: Psychic Powers.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Bonus TB against normal weapons, immune  to disease and poison."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"SnglwF3ayGuE7pZU"}
{"name":"Dark-sight","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">Some species are sensitive to different wavelengths of light than </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">man, and can detect sights otherwise invisible. A creature with this </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">trait sees normally even in areas of total darkness, and never takes </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 14.7165px;\">a penalty for fighting in areas of dim or no lighting.</span></span></p>","source":"","benefit":"Can see in darkness"},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"3742w5ItaQNmnuhV"}
{"name":"Deadly Natural Weapons","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature&rsquo;s natural attacks are powerful enough to crush plasteel or punch through armour. The creature gains all the benefits of the Natural Weapons trait (see page 137), except that its attacks no longer have the Primitive weapon quality.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Natural weapons are no longer primitive."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"wqlHKqnfCYz6iV83"}
{"name":"Fear","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait has an unnerving appearance. Some prey upon humanity&rsquo;s visceral terrors, while others depend on the inherent corruptive power of the Warp. The Fear trait always has an associated rating (1&ndash;4) to reflect how awful the creature is to behold; this is indicated by the number in parentheses (X). The higher the Fear rating, the harder it is for others to resist going insane from the encounter, as shown on Table 4&ndash;5: Fear Rating. When a character encounters a creature with this trait, the character must make a Willpower test with a penalty based on the creature&rsquo;s Fear rating. If he succeeds, the character suffers no ill effects; if he fails, he must roll on Table 8-11: Shock (see page 287), adding +10 to the roll for every degree of failure on the test.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Forces others to make Fear tests to avoid  Shock and Madness."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"s0BEnorgThEPe6M7"}
{"name":"Flyer","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait has the natural ability to fly, whether with broad leathery wings, strange warp energies, or inflatable gas sacs. The number in parentheses (X) indicates its speed when flying. This number replaces the creature&rsquo;s Agility bonus for movement actions while airborne. For more details on flying, see page 249 of Chapter VII: Combat.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Fly and enter any altitude."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"TtBq0rY52rcy4A4t"}
{"name":"From Beyond","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Some creatures are free from the limitations of normal physiology, having emerged from the impossible realm of the Warp or perhaps using bodies forged from cold metal and circuitry. Their minds are beyond the petty frailties and precarious sanity of a mortal mind. Such a creature is immune to Fear, Pinning, Insanity points, and psychic powers used to cloud, control, or delude its mind.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Immune to Fear, Pinning, Insanity points, and mind-affecting powers."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"ZYK37qeP2GFrFzhE"}
{"name":"Hoverer","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Creatures with this trait have a limited capability for flight, flying no higher than two metres. The number in parentheses (X) indicates its speed when hovering; this number replaces its Agility bonus for purposes of calculating Movement while airborne. For more details on flying, see page 249 of Chapter VII: Combat.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Fly and enter the hover altitude."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"2Ow4uHAcprxbhlAF"}
{"name":"Incorporeal","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature is insubstantial and weightless, able to pass through solid objects such as walls and weapons. Incorporeal creatures gain the Hoverer (6) trait and a +30 bonus on Stealth tests due to their ability to merge with objects and nearly silent movement. An Incorporeal creature is also immune to normal weapons, which simply pass ineffectually through its body. Daemons, psychic powers, Warp creatures, other Incorporeal creatures, and opponents armed with force weapons can all injure an Incorporeal creature normally. An Incorporeal creature cannot usually affect the mortal world, and thus cannot damage normal opponents unless it has a suitable special ability or talent. Certain devices can keep these creatures at bay, though, most notably a Void Shield or a spaceship&rsquo;s Gellar Field, which acts as an impenetrable barrier to them.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Insubstantial and weightless, cannot be affected by mundane weaponry."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"gX8RvYmuhhrDgjoF"}
{"name":"Machine","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">A creature with this trait is fashioned from </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">inorganic materials and is generally more </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">rigorous then fleshy beings. Machines </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">do not breathe, are immune to vacuum, </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">extremes of cold, and mind-influencing </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">psychic effects. Machines have a certain </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">number of Armour points (indicated by </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">the number in parentheses). This armour </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">stacks with worn armour, but not with the </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">Natural Armour trait, and can damage from </span></span><span style=\"font-family: sans-serif;\"><span style=\"font-size: 13.2448px;\">Fire (see page 243).</span></span></p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature gains immunities  and resistances."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"hAwHEjmUGlxwiPAT"}
{"name":"Mechanicus Implants","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>The character is a servant of the Machine-God, and has been entrusted with a suite of specialised implants:</p>\n<p><strong>Cranial CirCuitry</strong></p>\n<p>Cranial circuitry is a series of linked processors, implants, and cortical circuits that enhances mental capacities. Most sit within a housing bolted onto the skull, whilst others nestle within the brain itself.</p>\n<p><strong>Cyber-Mantle</strong></p>\n<p>The Cyber-mantle is a framework of metal, wires, and impulse transmitters bolted onto the spine and lower ribcage. As the initiate gains further cybernetics such as mechadendrites, the mantle acts as a sub-dermal anchorage point. Many in the Mechanicum often refer to it as &ldquo;the true flesh.&rdquo;</p>\n<p><strong>Electro-Graft</strong></p>\n<p>This small device is grafted into the nervous system, allowing the adept to better commune with the many holy mechanisms that are now part of his life. It comes in many forms, such as skull shunts, finger probes, or spine jacks, depending on the forge world.</p>\n<p><strong>Electoo Inductors</strong></p>\n<p>Electoo Inductors are palm-sized metal skin grafts that appear much like tattoos to the uninitiated. They are wired into the nervous system, where they derive power from the bioelectrical emanations of the flesh and the sacred mysteries of the Potentia Coil. With training, they can be used to emit or siphon power in many ways.</p>\n<p><strong>Potentia Coil</strong></p>\n<p>Cradled within the cyber-mantle is a power unit known as the Potentia Coil. This mass can store energy and produce various types of fields. Coils come in many types, from small crystal stack affairs to bulky electrical galvinators, and a trained user can manipulate the stored energy into a variety of attacks and unique effects.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Character has mechanical augmentations."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Nf8WlBdpsyN3rYwj"}
{"name":"Mind Lock","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Many flesh-constructs or mindless creatures are implanted with control mechanisms, complete with programmed behavioural instructions. This helps ensure the creature acts properly within its designed parameters, but also can lead to stalled actions when it faces circumstances for which it has no guidance. If faced with a situation outside of its programming and with no recognised master to issue orders, the creature must pass a Routine (+20) Intelligence test or be Stunned for 1 round. Due to its essentially mindless nature, at the GM&rsquo;s discretion it is immune to all Opposed Social tests.</p>","source":"","benefit":"If not properly controlled, character can  become Stunned."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"w4fUVEpjyG0HXzRJ"}
{"name":"Multiple Arms","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature has more than one pair of arms. The exact number of arms is indicated in parentheses (X), so a Genestealer with Multiple Arms (4) has four arms total. It gains a +10 bonus on Athletics tests involving climbing and swimming. In addition, for each full pair of arms it has (the Multiple Arms value divided by 2) it can make an additional attack as if wielding multiple melee weapons. In this case, the creature must either have natural weapons or actual melee weapons to wield for this to take effect. Note that a creature still requires the Two-Weapon Wielder (Melee or Ranged) talent to make multiple attacks in the same turn.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature gains extra attacks."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Iivqdzd5xl2TYejd"}
{"name":"Natural Armour","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature has a naturally tough hide or an exoskeleton, affording it some protection against attacks. The number in parentheses (X) indicates how many Armour points the creature gains to all locations. Natural Armour stacks with worn armour, but not with the Machine trait.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Gain additional Armour points to  all locations."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Bm9S175JV0ON7xoz"}
{"name":"Natural Weapons","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature has sharp claws, teeth, spines or some other natural weapon with which it can tear apart its foes. It counts as being armed even when not wielding weapons, with attacks that deal 1d10 points of damage plus its Strength bonus. The creature can make attacks with its Natural Weapons using its Weapon Skill, though it cannot Parry with its natural weapons, nor can it be disarmed unless, of course, its limbs are hacked off. In general, creatures with Natural Weapons are immune to the Power Field quality, as it is assumed they have enough teeth, claws, or spines to ignore a few being removed. Natural weapons have the Primitive (7) weapon quality unless stated otherwise in the profile.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Unarmed attacks deal 1d10+SB damage."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"YzQda5LE7MyDh7HY"}
{"name":"Phase","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait can transform its body into an insubstantial state, passing ghost-like through solid objects or barriers of any sort. As a Half Action, the creature may gain or remove the Incorporeal trait, becoming insubstantial or solid.</p>","source":"","benefit":"PhaseSwitch between incorporeal and corporeal as a Half Action."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"cQvM6bljzkBT4shr"}
{"name":"Psyker","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Whether due to unnatural influences, the study of forbidden lore, or simply sheer force of will, this individual is a psyker. Though this trait has no benefits on its own, it allows characters to purchase the Psyniscience skill and psychic powers. All psykers have a psy rating (or PR; see page 193) which is listed out for each NPC.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature has a psy rating of 1 or more."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"7HpG0ikuGwuB7Tqr"}
{"name":"Quadruped","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Quadrupeds are much quicker over a distance than their bipedal counterparts, and their movement is double that normally indicated by their Agility bonus (see page 245). This trait is intended to cover creatures that travel on their hind legs and forepaws, rapidly crossing surface terrain or tall foliage. Creatures with more than four legs may gain this trait as well, increasing their movement as indicated above but adding an additional 2 (after doubling) to their final movement rate for each set of legs beyond the first two pairs (i.e., +2 for 6 legs, +4 for 8 legs, etc.).</p>","source":"","benefit":"Movement equals ABÃ—2."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"RktGbkcEvaDlVGnV"}
{"name":"Regeneration","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Physiological enhancements, mutations, xenos physiology, and even Warp-corruption can all result in organisms that heal from injury at an inconceivable pace. Each round, at the start of its turn, the creature can make a Toughness test to remove an amount of damage indicated in the parentheses after the trait.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Test Toughness to remove 1 or more damage."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"vDnXRBrRLCpQbPv0"}
{"name":"Sanctioned","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>As part of the tithes every world owes the Imperium, each must collect all who show any sign of psychic abilities for the Black Ships to carry to Terra. There, the Adeptus Astra Telepathica conduct fearsome testing known as sanctioning for power levels, mental strength, and other factors that decide each psyker&rsquo;s fate. To survive is to have passed these tests, and gone on to serve the Emperor as a Sanctioned Psyker. If a Sanctioned character gains the Psyker elite advance, he does not gain the Corruption normally inflicted with that advance and starts at psy rating of 2 instead of 1.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Avoid Corruption from Psyker elite advance; start at psy rating 2."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"MK2VK29zP7LyUYn5"}
{"name":"Size","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Creatures come in one of ten different size categories, as shown on Table 4&ndash;6: Size. Size affects movement, how well the creature can hide and move undetected, and how easy or hard it is to strike in combat. When calculating movement, apply the size modifier first, and then other modifiers from other traits or talents (such as Quadruped). Note that a creature&rsquo;s movement cannot be reduced to less than 1.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Determines creature size and benefits."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"G7TCRIJ5veHU3Ztm"}
{"name":"Sonar Sense","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait perceives its surroundings by emitting uniquely toned pulses, allowing the creature to locate the position of any solid object within 30 metres. Other creatures within this 30 metre range that succeed on a Difficult (&ndash;10) Awareness skill can detect the oddly-pitched sounds echoing around them.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Perceive surroundings flawlessly  within 30 metres."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"hJWiazEYIu99erCK"}
{"name":"Soul Bound","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>The soul of this creature is bound to a higher power or being, in return for a measure of protection. When this trait is first gained, the entity to which the soul is bound must be decided. Many Imperial psykers, especially Astropaths, are soul bound to the Emperor, for example, whereas Chaos Sorcerers may be bound to one of the Ruinous Powers. A soul bound psyker rolls an extra die when forced to roll on Table 6&ndash;3: Perils of the Warp (see page 197), then replaces either the ones die or the tens die with the extra die he rolled to determine the final result.</p>\n<p>Upon becoming soul-bound, the psyker must choose one of the following effects: 3d10 Insanity points, the permanent loss of his sight, permanent loss of 1d10 points from one characteristic, or a random mutation. In addition, a soul bound character is permanently indebted to the entity, which undoubtedly entails all manner of other duties and consequences.&nbsp;</p>","source":"","benefit":"Bound to a particular group or creatures  in exchange for certain benefits."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"YhsX9FMYvI7tpKKz"}
{"name":"Stampede","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Whenever a creature with this trait fails a Willpower test, it automatically moves in a straight line forwards as far as possible, overrunning anything in its path until the source of danger is escaped or crushed under hoof. Anyone in the way suffers a single hit from the creature&rsquo;s Natural Weapons (or 1d5+SB Impact damage if it does not have that trait). One stampeding creature automatically causes all other creatures with the same trait within sight to stampede as well. The stampede lasts until the source of danger is no longer visible or for 1d10 minutes, whichever occurs last.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Failed Willpower test causes creature  to flee, trampling anything in its path."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"Vr55AaTMbMcp9u6T"}
{"name":"Stuff of Nightmares","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Some Warp entities are so terribly powerful that the willpower perpetuating their bodies in reality is almost impossible to break or disrupt. Such creatures count as having the Undying trait, and are completely immune to most environmental hazards, Blood Loss, and Stunning. They also ignore any Critical Effect other than one that would destroy them outright, unless it was caused by a psychic power, force weapon, or holy attack.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Become immune to most conditions that would harm normal creatures."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"TKveL9PixaumYORl"}
{"name":"Sturdy","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Sturdy creatures are hard to move, and thus gain a +20 bonus to tests made to resist Grappling and Knock Down actions, and uses of the Takedown talent.</p>","source":"","benefit":"+20 bonus to resist grapple, Knock Down,  and Takedown."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"065MGtpOdC3DjaTW"}
{"name":"Touched by  the Fates","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Where the naive might see only luck, those who have glimpsed the true nature of the galaxy can see when powers outside this realm have made their favour known. The NPC has a number of Fate points shown in parentheses (X). It can use these Fate points in exactly the same way as Player Characters and can even burn a Fate point to survive death and destruction at the GM&rsquo;s discretion. The NPC&rsquo;s attacks also use the rules for Righteous Fury.</p>","source":"","benefit":"NPC has Fate points."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"vrHr12vfs5wiqqO4"}
{"name":"Toxic","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>A creature with this trait has corrosive blood or other exotic defensive mechanisms that inflict harm when it is struck. A character that successfully deals damage to a Toxic creature in melee combat must make a Toughness test at the end of his turn with a penalty equal to 10 times the number in parentheses (X), or suffer 1d10 points of Energy damage not reduced by Armour or Toughness. For example, a creature with Toxic (4) would impose a &ndash;40 on Toughness tests. Some creatures carry additional effects with their toxins, or inflict more damage as indicated in their individual descriptions.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Gain poisonous attack."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"clglaSKjH3eXZ51o"}
{"name":"Undying","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>This creature has a strange and barely understood physiology. It cannot be harmed by diseases, poisons, or toxic effects. It also has no need to breathe, and thus can survive unaided in a vacuum.</p>","source":"","benefit":"The creature is immune to many environmental and natural dangers."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"HO7z53BA1nxTlMrT"}
{"name":"Unnatural Characteristic","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>One or more of the creature&rsquo;s characteristics is unnaturally enhanced. This is indicated by a number that is then added directly to the relevant Characteristic bonus. For example, a creature with a Strength of 41 normally has a Strength bonus of 4. If the creature had Unnatural Strength (3) then its Strength bonus increases to 7 (4+3). A creature can have this trait more than once, but each time must be applied to a new characteristic. Successful tests using a characteristic tied to this trait gain a number of bonus degrees of success equal to half the Unnatural Characteristic value.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Increases one characteristic bonus."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"FfBcIbIVSOg7lKva"}
{"name":"Unnatural Senses","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>The creature can perceive its surroundings using senses other than sight or hearing, such as special organs, fine hairs, or some other disturbing ability. This trait always includes a range in metres indicated by the number in parentheses (X).</p>","source":"","benefit":"Perceive surroundings by uncanny means."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"DQZmAlQm0SsrUMxB"}
{"name":"Warp Instability","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Most Warp-entities have a tenuous hold on reality, often maintained only by horror and bloodshed, and can be disrupted if sufficient harm can be done to their manifested forms. If a creature with this trait takes damage and does not deal any damage or Insanity points to another creature by the end of its next turn, it must make a Willpower test. The creature suffers 1 point of damage for failing, plus 1 additional point of damage for each degree of failure. If this would deal damage equal to (or in excess of) the creature&rsquo;s wounds, it is cast back into the Warp.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature must deal damage if damaged,  or be cast back into the Warp."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"RShpmp0Rs3OdEsLx"}
{"name":"Warp Weapons","permission":{"default":0,"Q8i5xjnghNCdqNHG":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":"<p>Creatures with this trait have weapons that are partially insubstantial, able to ignore such mundane things as armour or cover. Natural weapons and attacks made by a creature with this trait ignore physical armour, unless the armour is created from psychoactive materials or is somehow warded against the Warp. Force fields still work against these attacks normally.</p>","source":"","benefit":"Creature's attacks ignore armour."},"flags":{},"img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","effects":[],"_id":"P8PQsAOioVTzW1sW"}
